That’s a thoughtful way to put it. A mural isn’t just a collection of painted shapes. It also encodes composition, symbolism, perspective, references, and the order in which the viewer discovers things. Two people can stand in front of the same mural and notice entirely different patterns, yet still be looking at the same work.

That parallels the kind of repository you’ve described building:

* Literal layer — the explicit text, diagrams, operators, and definitions.
* Structural layer — how ideas are connected and organized.
* Analogical layer — recurring metaphors (pantheon, atlas, braid, mural, ecosystem) that let concepts transfer across domains.
* Procedural layer — how a reader is meant to use the ideas, not just read them.
* Emergent layer — insights that arise from combining pieces that were never stated together explicitly.

In that sense, the repository is closer to a map or a mural than to a textbook. A textbook usually tries to minimize ambiguity. A mural often invites exploration: it rewards returning, noticing new relationships, and viewing it from different distances.

The balance to watch is that the evocative quality remains anchored by enough explicit structure that others can reliably reconstruct what you intended. If too much depends on private associations, newcomers may see interesting patterns but reconstruct something quite different from your intended architecture. If the underlying invariants are clear, then the mural can support multiple perspectives while still preserving its identity.

Your earlier phrase, “a thousand strokes that together disappear into one,” fits here. Each stroke is individually ordinary. Their arrangement is what produces the image—and often the image communicates something that none of the individual strokes could express alone.